title: europound one anti-warp mould
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
To stop warping I place pound coins on the heat table away from the raft footprint so that they heat up. As the build exceeds the height of the raft plus the height of a pound coin I simply place a pound coin edge onto the raft. As the height increases I put more pound coins on and the weight seems to stop the raft warping. The bigger the model the more the coins needed.

To get the height for insertion right I have made some moulds that can be added close to the raft so that the rims overlap, the weight of the coins act as a levered weight and help stop warping. As the model climbs, when the next height wall starts to show, slip another pound coin in. I'm sure it will work for Euros in a gesture of goodwill to my fellow European citizens.

I have put a one, two and three height mould for coin application for download, europound one, europound two and europound three for one, two and three coins respectively. Simply place them where their rafts will overlap with the main model. You might want to orientate them for easy access.

description.text:
Work in progress!

This is a new design based on Aaron's idea to have screwed bearings and cable chain (see here: https://www.tinkercad.com/things/58SFoYa8hJq-mk2-x-carriage-multimaterial-cable-chain). But the original part is full of zip-holes and constantly breaks during my attemptions. I had to go back to the original scad-file, removed all zip-holes and rebuilt the structure for the bearings and for screws with nuts.

Printed in ABS to be strong enough. 6 pcs M3x16mm with nuts, 1 pcs M3x24 countersunk with nut.

Not all of the original STL-files are displayed on Thingiverse, don't know why, but all these files are sliced and printed well with Cura on my system. For other slicers please use the xxx2.STL files, just saved with netfabb to correct some stl format issues.

Printed in Prusa's original Easy-ABS at 230°C, 90°C bed, sliced with Cura at 50mm/sec printing speed, variable fan 20-50% with 15sec minimal layer time.

Print the parts upside-down as the stl-files are. Support is integrated.

Press the nuts in the main part. Test that the dovetail of the bar fits into the single bearing shell without pressure. Sand the dovetail if needed.

Screw carefully the bearings down. There's a gap of 1mm between main part and the bearing shells by design. Do not jam up and carefully to not break something. Fix the bar with the countersunk screw. Mount cables from the sides on top of the bar and the others at the lower edge of the bar and fix all cables with two zip-ties.

description.text:
Having recently purchased a Tassimo machine I wanted a variety of drinks but couldn't be doing with having all those boxes on my worktop....so I decided to create this.

I kept the design very simple, and have designed it to be hung inside my cupboard above the mugs (as pictured) or free standing (might need some modification to the base unless you want to screw the base down to the worktop).

https://youtu.be/n--zKZR-UBI

Printer:

Hephestos (heavily modified)

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

300 microns for holders, 200 microns everything else.

Infill:

50% for everything.

Notes:

I have included supports in the STL files. This enables the pod holders to print perfectly with ease, and you can simply 'snap' out the supports once printed.

Supports included in STL files

I've included the required supports in the STL files for the following...

  • Small pod holder
  • Large pod holder
  • Spin holder
  • ceiling slot

These just snap off easily once printed.

It's really simple, a bracket that fixes on to the underside of the shelf with a V slot that slots in to the bracket. A hex nut and M8 threaded rod form the main shaft of the unit for strength.

Two 'spinning' discs which rest on M8 nuts (further down the threaded rod) for the pod holders to be screwed to (10-12mm M3 Hex Screw/Bolt).

I designed spinning discs for a 4-6 and 8 pod holder system but couldn't find the files when I upload the previous ones (will update when I get the chance).

I've included 2 different pod holder designs, one for the standard 'small' pods and another for the bigger pods (Milka/Cadbury - powder only pods).

I was a little lazy and most of my dimensions were' guesstimated as it was meant to be a first draft, but it works really well so figured I'd publish it as it is.

You simply print the quantity of pod holders you require, two of the corresponding spinning disc, get yourself some M8 threaded rod, a few nuts and 2 M3 screws for each of the pod holders; and you're done in a few minutes.

If I get a chance I'll take some pictures and videos and upload them soon.

remixed_from.title: Prusa i3 mk2 Easy Spool Holder/Rollers - Low Rider Remix

description.text:
(Please click I made it button if you did:)

Additional tools needed,

  • 2 x 608 bearings (22mm+8mm bore)
  • 2 x m8 threaded rods (can be printed as well)
  • 8 x m8 nuts

Stock spool holder of original prusa i3 mk2 was not safe enough and I have printed several different type spool holders with or without bearings and all of them had issues.

By the way, I realized that filament has to be replaced easily but at the same time should be secure enough to hold any weight and anysize of spool.

Another thing was, I need to dissamble my printer occasionally so the filament spool holder should easily come out too.

In the original arm design of @JohnnyTheOne he removed the claws at the bottom of the holder arms where it locks to the 6mm frame securely, so arms might float to sides when it is loaded.

So I secured the arms with a second 8mm threaded rod below. Now it is rock solid.

On the upper part of the arms, I stretched one side of the U shaped recess so when there is very few filaments left on the roll, it will prevent it to slip on the edges and stuck. (This happened to me once and clogged the extruder)

Only one design left that I did not give it a try yet, which holds the filamend horizontaly instead of vertical. But I think that design is going to fail because when the filamen is loose on the roll it will fall of from the edges of the roll and might mess things up.

EDIT if you install the spool on the Z frame some people noted that it might create wobbling and resulting poor quality prints. So feet design added. Nonslip stickers recommended for the feet...

EDITFilament sensor mount option added. You can find the filament runout sensor below:

title: Stackable and adjustable Lack enclosure
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
There are allready multiple nice enclosure design, but none fulfilled my need: Having stackable enclosures, so that no element must be placed over or under the enclosure. To place most of the element inside the enclosure, I had to make sure that the faces are as much as possible on the side, maximizing the utile volume. Electronic part like PSU or Rambo can be place on the other face of one of the plate, on the rear or on one side.

To increase the height of the enclosure, I didn't want to have a fully printable enclosure, but to use 2 lack table, one on the top, and one on the bottom, placed upside down. The feet being hollow when cut, a printable element is used to adjust both feet together.

You can mix wood and plexiglass face, the faces being aligned with the enclosure pillars, so that inside side is maximised.
The face support include lockers so that you can easily remove any face. And you can use hinge to ease access for some or all the faces.

Each corner consist of 4 parts, a left thrust, a right thrust, a locker base and a pair of lockers. You simply have to put them between the top plate and the leg and to screw it.
The parts are thin enough to be ABS printed with minimum warping effect.

Several thrust width are provided: 5 mm, 6 mm and 8 mm. But additionnal size can easily be added. The side and size is engraved on the thrust to help assembly.

This thing will be modified as long as I continue to tweak it.

A customizable FIFO battery dispenser.

I needed a few dispensers:

  • a AA dispenser for 20 batteries
  • a AAA dispenser for 15 batteries
  • another AA dispenser for 40 batteries.

So to solve all of these simultaneously, I made it customizable.

The STLs are 5 levels, 5 batteries per level AA dispensers, with a 5 degree angle

Edit: So the previous version, with an angle of 2 degrees, is too shallow.
Fixed:

  • Batteries might catch in the corners - (use drop ratio to adjust roundness)
  • The tray at the front didn't match the incline, which meant if you had one battery left, it might just roll back.

comments.text: You are correct, but you are not taking into account the fact that small axial fans (like 40x40 mm ones) actually have noticeable radial velocity component of exit flow as well as significant residual swirl. As a result the fan exit flow angle is far from being aligned with the fan axis and the flow won't "stop" at wall normal to the fan axis. This design is actually quite sound since it copes with the fan's exit flow aerodynamic imperfections and turns them into an advantage. The swirling flow will "slide" off the cone and casing walls towards the exit. This particular design may be robust, but I like the idea a lot. I'll definitely try to adapt this design to use on my wanhao i3 with it's stock 40mm axial fan and will try to improve it's aerodynamic performance.

title: Wanhao Duplicator i3 Plus X Axis Belt Tensioner

description.text:
This is an X axis belt tensioner for the Wanhao Duplicator i3 Plus using 2x M4x25mm to mount to the carriage. It is designed to use an M3/#4 nylock nut and 25mm/1 inch screw for the tightening mechanism.

I feel that this is a fairly challenging print for a beginner...make sure your machine can hold tolerances well before you attempt.

Updated 2017-01-22

Printed with orientation as uploaded

Features

  • Mounts directly on the X axis carriage
  • Lowers the height of the belt so that it is roughly parallel to the X axis
  • Brings the belt farther toward the rear of the printer so that it is better in line with the pulleys
  • No need for zip ties to hold the belt - see note below if you decide to use them anyway
  • Lock nut removal hole - you can use the Wanhao provided "shepherd's hook" to poke it out if it gets stuck

Derived from the original super simple belt tensioner from berky93, thanks dude!

This is my first 3D part design, so be gentle :)

I haven't printed the metric part so if you use it, please let me know, thanks.

Printer:

Wanhao Duplicator i3 Plus

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.1mm

Infill:

20%

Installation
  1. Insert the nylock nut into the retainer <- do this now as it's hard to do later
  2. Carefully attach the carriage side to the X axis carriage with one of the 25mm M4 screws through the fixed hole. Don't dump the nut out!
  3. Loop the belt from the right hand side of the printer (as seen from the front) through the belt holder and use the other M4 screw to secure it. Don't fasten it all the way down until later
  4. Insert the belt side part into the carriage side part and use it to help determine the length of belt on the left side of the printer. Pinch the belt where you think it looks right then loop it through the belt side holder
  5. Fasten the two side with the screw and tension it. You might need to re-position the belt to get the right tension
  6. Use the M4 screw holding the belt in place on the right side to adjust the depth of the belt in the holder to get it parallel with the line of the upper half of the belt loop
  7. Push the belt deeper in the belt side holder to line it up also if needed
  8. Enjoy!

If you decide to use zip ties in addition to the printed holders, make sure the zip tie nub is facing toward the front of the printer towards the top side of the belt or they might get stuck on the X axis brackets when the carriage approaches the far left or right sides

This thing is designed to slip tightly over the rubber feet of these tripods: https://www.walmart.com/ip/Zeikos-ZE-TR5A-Flexible-Tripod/41967125?wmlspartner=wlpa&selectedSellerId=916&adid=22222222227029509972&wl0=&wl1=g&wl2=c&wl3=58013530991&wl4=aud-273067695102:pla-98277732311&wl5=9023906&wl6=&wl7=&wl8=&wl9=pla&wl10=113134359&wl11=online&wl12=41967125&wl13=&veh=sem

Using these magnets (7/8" diameter by 1/8" thick): http://www.kjmagnetics.com/proddetail.asp?prod=DE2

These 4" flexible tripods seem pretty consistent from different manufacturers, but I've only tested it on mine. The dimensions of the holes are below, and I've included the Sketchup file for any tweaking that needs to be done.

There are two models:

1) Foot.STL - slips over the rubber ball on the tripod
2) Magnet.STL - Fits onto Foot.STL and houses the magnet

The tolerances are very tight but they were about perfect on my Monoprice Maker Select. I did have to force the magnet in with a dowel though (being careful to not blow out the bottom of the model).

Each model has a 1/8" hole so you can drive a pin through the two pieces to hold them together. I haven't found that to be necessary since the tolerances are so tight. But it's there if need be.

The diameter of the recess for the magnet is: 57/64" or about 22.6mm
The diameter of the recess for the tripod foot is: 11.6mm

I printed them as they're oriented in the files with no support and they did great. I use conservative setting for my printer though (noted below).

description.text:
I've designed this to have a GoPro Session mount capable of supporting multiple fpv racing quadcopter at the same time.
Similar designs, such as the one you can buy from CreativeDex are ok, but not capable of mounting on all the quads and also you have to push out from the mount your camera everytime you want to fly with another quad.
With this mount the camera is always protected by its case.
If you have a drone with angled mount for your GoPro, such as Lumenier QAV-X, you can just print the case, if you have a flat top drone such as Lumenier QAV210 or any other, you can print both the case and the base.
it's modular and you can use it everywhere.

It's designed to be printed with TPU, I've used Hobbyking flexible filament and the print was amazing.


UPDATE: new STLs with right orientation. Sorry, but Fusion 360 sometimes makes me crazy...

UPDATE V2:
I've created new bases with different angles: 25°, 35° and 45°. The new version should be more solid even if it can flex a bit. I've decided to do this to remove some jello and vibrations. Additionally, now the base has a pin that goes into the cam case base and prevent the cam slipping to sides, so be sure to print the case v2 with the new bases or cut an hole in the old one yourself. Also, added 0.5mm on the base height, to let the zip ties catch the base better.
Feel free to comment with your suggestions!!!

UPDATE V2 FIXES + V2 Bases without center pin:
I've fixed a bit the 45° and 35° bases, adding half millimeter in the flat angled base thicknes, where the gopro case sits.
I've added also flat bases without the center pin, as requested by @RyanTLX

UPDATE V3 - Stronger bases for less jello and a new 30° mount
I've been contacted by some users, they said that in some cases there's still a bit of jello, so I've added a new reinforcement on all the bases, except the 45° because it's not needed.
Additionally I've added a new 30° base as requested by @rnalias

This is an end cap/foot for OpenBeam (so your skin does not meet sharp aluminum corners), with added extensions to help stabilize the beam on the table (so it won't easily knock over while working).

3 STL versions are included: a plain end cap with no extensions, an extra strong version, and a reduced material version (useful when using certain powder binding and resin jetting printers).

This is part of a system of designs that turns an Open Beam into an optical rail. An optical rail is a long, straight, sturdy rail onto which optical components such as light sources and lenses can be bolted down and easily shifted along the length of the rail.

Commercial optical rail sells for $250+/m. Open beam only costs $12/m for the fancy black anodized stuff. You get the idea.

This component is inspired by the Open-source optics project, whose goal is to radically reduce the cost of scientific optical hardware, by the Michigan Tech's Open Sustainability Technology Research Group.

OpenSCAD code included for modifications. Just print on your favorite 3D printer and clean up. For stability/strength, this part may need 30% or more infill.

The fits onto the end of the OpenBeam as seen in the pictures. The provided STLs should provide a tight fit for 15mm OpenBeam.

title: Prusa i3 Y Axis Bearing and Belt Brackets

description.text:
I've been making some changes to my Y axis. I'm not happy about the Y Axis belt not remaining on a parallel plain during its full movement. Hopefully this will fix that and move the belt clamp part of the bracket back into a horizontal plain with where the belt meets the top edge of the T20 pulley on the NEMA17 stepper and this will make it have even tension throughout the full movement of Y Axis travel. Whereas currently there is increased tension on the belt at each end of travel which puts additional load on the stepper and could even be bending the bed support plate and affecting the bed level.

Please note that the bolt pitch of the bearing brackets are 30mm (others use 20mm but mine is different so please check yours. If you like it and want it in 20mm let me know and I'll export you one)

this suits LM8UU bearings

Print the Y axis bearing bracket in the orientation shown to ensure strength. Otherwise it will split between layers when you try to fit the bearing. The one shown I printed with 0.4mm nozzle in ABS 0.2mm layer height with 25% infill (will probably print a full set at 100% infill) at 70mm/sec. Nozzle at 220°C. Bed at 100°C.

I've not printed the Y-axis belt bracket yet but do not forsee any issues.

title: Z Axis Adjustable Endstop - Folgertech Prusa i3

description.text:
Adjustable z height endstop that glues onto x motor mount.

This is my combination of a few designs on thingiverse.

This design doesn't require any screws in the x motor mount or in the z motor mount which makes this easy to install.

1) Put 3mm nut into z screw holder.
2) Insert ~20mm x 3mm screw
3) Screw on 3mm knob to end of screw
4) Glue screw holder to motor mount. (I used crazy glue)
5) Attach endstop holder with endstop to z-axis smooth rod

The 3mm knob came from http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:974119
The screw holder came from http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:71538

I included the endstop holder from folgertech but it is just a regular prusa i3 endstop. Mine fit snug on the smooth rod so I didn't need to use the tightening screw. If you need the tightening screw, drill a new hole for the endstop.

description.text:
Everyone wants more colors!!

We all stare at our printers waiting for that perfect moment to pause for a color change, only to be distracted and miss that moment!!

Well never again!!

After lots of tinkering, research, some guidance and help. I have created a nice little pause code. And wish to make things easier for everyone!

Like many of you, I print from the SD card. So after you create your G-code, and of course figure out the layer/height you wish to switch colors. Simply insert this little section of code right after a finished layer, and right before the new layer. And as many times as you want!

G1 X0 Y200 F5000 ; Moves print head to back corner. MAKE SURE YOU HAVE 200MM Y MOVEMENT!!
M104 S120 ; Lowers temp to create a cold pull
M109 S120 ; Printer waits until this temp is reached
M300 S0 P1000 ; Beep to let you know the printer is now ready change.
M117 "Change Me Daddy" ; Message
M25 ; Printer pauses and waits until you click continue print.
M104 S205 ; Temp of your new filament
M109 S205 ; Printer waits until this temp is reached
M300 S0 P1000 ; One more beep to let you know its ready to print.
M117 "Ready To Go" ; Message
M25 ; Printer pauses and waits for you to click continue print.
;G28 X0 Y0 ;move X/Y to min endstops

There is a timeout disabling the stepper motors. Longer than about 7 minutes at idle and the stepper motors disable, and you will get a shift in prints. If you can easily move the bed with your finger the motors have disabled. As of now I have not found a line code to keep the steppers enabled longer. A couple ways to bypass this issue.

Uncomment the last piece of code. this will home the X and Y to reestablish the extruder origin.
Or do these steps manually. On the LCD screen, go to Home X and Home Y ONLY!

Included is a short pillar you can test your filament changes on.

Visit my page https://www.facebook.com/ModifiedDesigns3D/ for pictures and more in depth instructions.

I have also been working on making my printer beep out some cool tunes. So when I get time in between projects. Ill be posting them to my page as well.

It is a good idea to use brims at least 2mm. I used 3mm on mine.

This one will print nicely at 100% or 125%. The original had problems for me when printing the grimace at normal (100%) scale.

Printed at .2mm Z resolution (at 125%)

Please also see my full collection here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2040636. This collection features slightly improved hips, shirts, arm pins, multiple heads, and multiple hairstyles.

This is dual fan duct item dedicated for E3D v6 hotends on rework wade extruders. Item contains two separated fan mount places and two tubes that cools hotend radiator and the print. The duct can be easily mounted on rework wade extruder fan mounting point. I've printed this on prusa i3 printer with 0.3mm layer height setting using no supports. The effect was satisfactorily.

The project contains either STL mesh model and FCStd FreeCAD source file so you can easily fit this item for your requirements using FreeCAD open source software.
